---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { estimateApr } from "../../lib/calc/apr";

const title = "APR Tool (estimate APR with fees and compare offers)";
const description =
  "A practical APR tool to compare loans by including upfront fees, plus guidance on what APR means and how to use it safely. Educational use only.";

const exampleLoan = 20000;
const exampleTerm = 60;
const rateA = 7.99;
const feeA = 0;
const rateB = 7.49;
const feeB = 800;
const offerA = estimateApr({ loanAmount: exampleLoan, nominalRatePercent: rateA, termMonths: exampleTerm, fees: feeA });
const offerB = estimateApr({ loanAmount: exampleLoan, nominalRatePercent: rateB, termMonths: exampleTerm, fees: feeB });
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/apr-tool">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">APR tool</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>APR tool</h1>
    <p>
      Use this APR tool to estimate the cost of a loan when fees are involved, and compare offers under consistent assumptions. This is an
      educational estimate, not an official lender disclosure.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/apr-calculator">Open the APR calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/how-to-find-your-apr">How to find your APR</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What to enter</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Loan amount</li>
      <li>Interest rate</li>
      <li>Term</li>
      <li>Upfront fees (origination, points)</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Tip: keep assumptions consistent across offers. If one lender quotes a different term or includes taxes/insurance in a "payment"
      figure, normalize inputs so you're comparing like with like.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What APR is doing (plain English)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Fees can make a loan more expensive even if the interest rate is the same. APR tries to express that cost as an annualized rate by
      accounting for money you pay upfront (fees/points) relative to the cash you actually receive.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Because fees are often "front-loaded," APR is most useful when you expect to keep the loan for a meaningful portion of the term.
      If you will refinance or move quickly, a break-even approach can be more informative than a single APR number.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Example: compare two offers</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(exampleLoan)} for {exampleTerm} months. Offer A is {pct2.format(rateA)}% with no fees. Offer B is
      {pct2.format(rateB)}% with a {money0.format(feeB)} fee. The APR tool estimates the APR after fees and shows how close the payments are.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Offer</th>
            <th class="num">Rate</th>
            <th class="num">Fees</th>
            <th class="num">Payment</th>
            <th class="num">APR</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>A</td>
            <td class="num">{pct2.format(rateA)}%</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(feeA)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(offerA.payment)}</td>
            <td class="num">{offerA.aprPercent == null ? "N/A" : `${pct2.format(offerA.aprPercent)}%`}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>B</td>
            <td class="num">{pct2.format(rateB)}%</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(feeB)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(offerB.payment)}</td>
            <td class="num">{offerB.aprPercent == null ? "N/A" : `${pct2.format(offerB.aprPercent)}%`}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Even a lower rate can have a higher APR if fees are large relative to the loan amount.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Break-even intuition</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If a lower rate comes with fees, the break-even point is when the monthly savings offset the upfront cost. Use the calculator to
      compare total dollars paid over the number of months you expect to keep the loan, not just over the full term.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">When APR is less useful</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>If you expect to refinance or sell quickly, compare total dollars over that short horizon.</li>
      <li>If one offer includes bundled products (insurance, add-ons), remove those fees before comparing.</li>
      <li>If the loan has variable rates, model multiple rate paths instead of relying on a single APR.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Cash-to-close vs financed fees</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Paid upfront:</strong> you bring more cash to closing but keep the loan balance lower.</li>
      <li><strong>Financed:</strong> you roll fees into the balance, increasing total cost and sometimes the payment.</li>
      <li>APR can rise in either case; confirm how fees are handled before comparing offers.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to use results</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>APR helps compare offers with different fees.</li>
      <li>Also compare cash-to-close and total dollars paid over your likely time horizon.</li>
      <li>If you refinance early, APR may not be the best single metric.</li>
    </ul>
    <h3 style="margin:16px 0 8px">Common pitfalls</h3>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Comparing different terms (a 3-year vs 5-year loan) without realizing the trade-off.</li>
      <li>Ignoring fees that are paid out-of-pocket versus rolled into the balance.</li>
      <li>Comparing APR but not comparing the dollar cost over the time you'll actually keep the loan.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: apples-to-apples comparisons</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Keep term, loan amount, and rate type consistent.</li>
      <li>Include all upfront fees and points.</li>
      <li>Compare total dollars paid over your expected time horizon.</li>
      <li>Note whether fees are paid out-of-pocket or rolled in.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Why is APR higher than the rate?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      APR includes certain fees, so it can be higher than the nominal rate even if the payment looks similar.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is APR always the best metric?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      APR is a good summary for long-term comparisons, but short-term borrowers should also compare total cost over their horizon.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">What fees are included?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      The tool includes the fees you input. Always confirm the lender's official disclosure for the final APR.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{' '}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-is-an-apr-en-67/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          What is APR?</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/apr-calculator">Run comparisons</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/interest-rate-apr-calculator">Interest rate vs APR</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/apr-calculator-payment">APR and payment</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/apr">APR hub</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">Educational use only. Not financial advice.</p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">Last updated: 2026-01-28</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
